00:00:06.120 --> 00:00:07.720
SPEAKER: I am super
excited to have

00:00:07.720 --> 00:00:09.760
Clara Hemphill, founder of
Inside Schools, here with us

00:00:09.760 --> 00:00:10.260
today.

00:00:10.260 --> 00:00:13.540
She's a font of knowledge,
and it's exciting.

00:00:13.540 --> 00:00:17.560
So just a little bit about
Clara so you know who she is.

00:00:17.560 --> 00:00:22.390
She leads the Center of New
York City Affairs policy work

00:00:22.390 --> 00:00:25.030
on economic segregation
of the city's schools,

00:00:25.030 --> 00:00:27.730
examining why there are schools
with high concentrations

00:00:27.730 --> 00:00:31.030
of poverty even in
mixed-income neighborhoods.

00:00:31.030 --> 00:00:33.310
The "New York Times" called
her three books designed

00:00:33.310 --> 00:00:35.330
to help parents choose
good elementary, middle,

00:00:35.330 --> 00:00:37.030
and high schools
for their children

00:00:37.030 --> 00:00:40.270
the most definitive guides
to the city's schools.

00:00:40.270 --> 00:00:42.310
And "New York"
magazine called her one

00:00:42.310 --> 00:00:45.860
of the 200 most influential
New Yorkers for her work

00:00:45.860 --> 00:00:48.960
in empowering parents.

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:51.150
Previously as a reporter
and editorial writer

00:00:51.150 --> 00:00:53.880
for New York "Newsday," she
shared the Pulitzer Prize

00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:55.689
for local reporting.

00:00:55.689 --> 00:00:58.230
"New York" magazine called her
writing on the homeless worthy

00:00:58.230 --> 00:00:59.767
of Dickens.

00:00:59.767 --> 00:01:02.100
She was a foreign correspondent
for the Associated Press

00:01:02.100 --> 00:01:05.780
and a producer for CBS
News based in Rome.

00:01:05.780 --> 00:01:07.760
She has two children,
both now grown,

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:10.100
and they both attended New
York City public schools

00:01:10.100 --> 00:01:12.800
from kindergarten
through high school.

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:17.950
So please join me in welcoming
Clara Hemphill to talk

00:01:17.950 --> 00:01:19.930
about the public
schools and navigating

00:01:19.930 --> 00:01:22.180
the very segregated and
ridiculously complex

00:01:22.180 --> 00:01:23.380
New York City school system.

00:01:23.380 --> 00:01:24.203
Thank you.

00:01:24.203 --> 00:01:25.682
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:29.457 --> 00:01:30.540
CLARA HEMPHILL: Thank you.

00:01:30.540 --> 00:01:32.740
I'm really glad to be here.

00:01:32.740 --> 00:01:36.690
I wrote the first edition
of this book 20 years ago

00:01:36.690 --> 00:01:41.880
when my children
were three and one.

00:01:41.880 --> 00:01:43.290
They're now all grown up.

00:01:43.290 --> 00:01:47.010
And I thought, gee, I can
