00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:20.440
Best Public Pre-K and Elementary
Schools" on sale in the back.

00:02:20.440 --> 00:02:21.300
I hope you buy it.

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:22.200
Thanks very much.

00:02:28.350 --> 00:02:31.470
Why should you
choose public school?

00:02:31.470 --> 00:02:34.140
Why do public schools matter?

00:02:34.140 --> 00:02:39.720
And one of the things that
the last election showed us,

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:45.370
the national elections, is how
divided we are as a country.

00:02:45.370 --> 00:02:47.270
And public schools,
when they work,

00:02:47.270 --> 00:02:49.980
have the ability to
bring us together,

00:02:49.980 --> 00:02:52.800
to help us understand
one another.

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:56.160
And we need the public
schools now more than ever.

00:02:56.160 --> 00:02:58.200
This picture here is
an example of a school

00:02:58.200 --> 00:02:59.700
that I think brings
people together.

00:02:59.700 --> 00:03:02.440
It's Dos Puentes in
Washington Heights.

00:03:02.440 --> 00:03:05.360
If you know Washington Heights,
on the east side of Broadway

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:07.680
is mostly Dominican
Spanish-speaking kids.

00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:10.890
On the west side is mostly
English-speaking kids.

00:03:10.890 --> 00:03:12.840
Dos Puentes brings
these kids together

00:03:12.840 --> 00:03:18.720
in a dual-language program,
where they speak English

00:03:18.720 --> 00:03:23.550
half the time and they
speak Spanish half the time.

00:03:23.550 --> 00:03:26.580
And it's a really
lovely, lovely school

00:03:26.580 --> 00:03:31.860
and an example of how
children can learn together.

00:03:31.860 --> 00:03:34.440
One of the things I like
about it is that the parents'

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:36.120
meetings are given--
sometimes they're

00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:38.550
given in Spanish with
English translation,

00:03:38.550 --> 00:03:41.280
and sometimes they're
given in English

00:03:41.280 --> 00:03:43.140
with Spanish translation.

00:03:43.140 --> 00:03:45.540
And one of the things I liked
about going to that school

00:03:45.540 --> 00:03:48.030
was having the experience
of being somebody

00:03:48.030 --> 00:03:50.550
who didn't understand the
language that was spoken

00:03:50.550 --> 00:03:52.450
and had to have the translation.

00:03:52.450 --> 00:03:57.360
So that's one of the schools in
the book that I can recommend.

00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:00.300
Public schools are just
about the only place

00:04:00.300 --> 00:04:03.840
besides jury duty
and the subways

00:04:03.840 --> 00:04:09.210
where people of different races,
incomes, and backgrounds mix.

00:04:09.210 --> 00:04:12.300
This is Ella Baker
School on the Upper East

00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:16.860
Side, which is open
to children by lottery

00:04:16.860 --> 00:04:20.310
from all five Boroughs.

00:04:20.310 --> 00:04:21.540
So it's not a zoned school.

00:04:21.540 --> 00:04:23.850
It's a city-wide school.

00:04:23.850 --> 00:04:28.050
And the great education
philosopher John Dewey,

00:04:28.050 --> 00:04:30.150
at the turn of the
last century, wrote

00:04:30.150 --> 00:04:31.920
that "schools should
teach children

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:36.060
to be social beings
trained for leadership

00:04:36.060 --> 00:04:40.470
as well as obedience, trained
so they can be voting citizens

00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:44.400
in a multi-ethnic democracy,
not passive subjects.

00:04:44.400 --> 00:04:47.820
"Teachings them to be social
beings without letting them

00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:49.810
mingle with other
children," Dewey wrote,

00:04:49.810 --> 00:04:52.590
is like teaching them
to swim without letting

00:04:52.590 --> 00:04:55.750
them go in the water.

00:04:55.750 --> 00:04:59.280
I remember talking
to a Jewish father

00:04:59.280 --> 00:05:03.120
some time ago who was
choosing between a Jewish day

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:09.750
school and a public school.

00:05:09.750 --> 00:05:11.490
And I told him,
yes, I understand

00:05:11.490 --> 00:05:14.820
you want your child to
learn about your religious

00:05:14.820 --> 00:05:17.370
traditions, Hebrew.

00:05:17.370 --> 00:05:20.010
Your values are very
important to you.

00:05:20.010 --> 00:05:22.000
But if you send your
child to public school,

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.410
I guarantee he will meet
at least one child who

00:05:25.410 --> 00:05:27.840
celebrates Ramadan.

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:30.230
And a child who
celebrates Ramadan

00:05:30.230 --> 00:05:32.610
will meet at least
one child who--

00:05:32.610 --> 00:05:33.390
he interrupted me.

00:05:33.390 --> 00:05:34.800
He said, yeah, I get the idea.

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:36.000
I get the point.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.070
And that clinched
the deal for him.

00:05:40.070 --> 00:05:45.600
This is PS 75 on the
Upper West Side, which

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:48.480
serves both Columbia
University professors' children

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:51.225
but also children who live
in public housing nearby.

00:05:57.110 --> 00:06:00.260
A lot of the schools in the book
are ordinary zoned neighborhood

00:06:00.260 --> 00:06:02.030
schools, no special application.

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:04.130
You just sign your child up.

00:06:04.130 --> 00:06:07.070
This is PS 180 in Harlem.

00:06:07.070 --> 00:06:09.710
In some ways, it's
an ordinary school.

00:06:09.710 --> 00:06:11.430
Test scores are nothing special.

00:06:11.430 --> 00:06:13.590
It's just sort of
an ordinary school.

00:06:13.590 --> 00:06:15.740
But a mother told
me, I feel like I'm

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:18.860
part of a community and
a neighborhood in a way

00:06:18.860 --> 00:06:20.390
that I never expected--

00:06:20.390 --> 00:06:22.940
the pleasure of making friends
with other parents, sharing

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:25.250
babysitters and
after-school pickups,

00:06:25.250 --> 00:06:27.170
even sharing holiday meals.

00:06:27.170 --> 00:06:30.830
So I live on the
Upper East Side,

00:06:30.830 --> 00:06:33.590
and I never felt I really
lived in the neighborhood

00:06:33.590 --> 00:06:36.680
until I had children and sent
them to the public schools.

00:06:36.680 --> 00:06:42.000
And there's something about
sharing the responsibilities

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.170
of parenthood with other
people in the neighborhood that

00:06:45.170 --> 00:06:51.210
really makes you feel like
you belong in a neighborhood.

00:06:51.210 --> 00:06:53.347
Now I know some of
you will say, oh,

00:06:53.347 --> 00:06:54.930
that's all very well
and good for you.

00:06:54.930 --> 00:06:56.700
You live on the Upper East Side.

00:06:56.700 --> 00:07:01.290
But what if you live in the
Bronx or in central Brooklyn?

00:07:01.290 --> 00:07:06.780
One of the questions I got ahead
of time for this talk was--

00:07:06.780 --> 00:07:08.820
this is a quote from one of you.

00:07:08.820 --> 00:07:12.990
"Public school is not a viable
option for every New Yorker."

00:07:12.990 --> 00:07:17.610
This parent was zoned for
133 in District 5 in Harlem.

00:07:17.610 --> 00:07:20.640
"I cannot in good conscience
send my children to my zoned

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:21.630
school.

00:07:21.630 --> 00:07:24.060
Charter is also not
an option if you're

00:07:24.060 --> 00:07:27.630
against rote memorization and
some other very regimented

00:07:27.630 --> 00:07:31.350
tactics they use
to teach students."

00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:35.310
It's true that there
aren't as many good schools

00:07:35.310 --> 00:07:37.530
in poor and working-class
neighborhoods

00:07:37.530 --> 00:07:39.630
as there are in
rich neighborhoods.

00:07:39.630 --> 00:07:42.840
And racial and
economic segregation

00:07:42.840 --> 00:07:44.910
is a reality, as
those of you who

00:07:44.910 --> 00:07:50.080
were at Nikole Hannah-Jones'
talk some time ago remember.

00:07:50.080 --> 00:07:51.840
But in researching
the book, we found

00:07:51.840 --> 00:07:57.150
good schools in every one of
the city's 32 school districts,

00:07:57.150 --> 00:08:00.420
not as many as we'd
like, but at least a few.

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:02.850
And we found some
pleasant surprises.

00:08:02.850 --> 00:08:06.960
You don't have to live on Park
Avenue to find a good school.

00:08:09.840 --> 00:08:12.030
I also want to say that
not all the charter

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:14.820
schools are rigid places
where children are

00:08:14.820 --> 00:08:16.350
expected to act like robots.

00:08:16.350 --> 00:08:19.080
There are some
progressive schools,

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:22.680
where children learn through
exploration and play.

00:08:22.680 --> 00:08:25.920
And not all the charter
schools are the same, just

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:29.430
the way all the ordinary public
schools are not the same.

00:08:29.430 --> 00:08:31.020
What about segregation?

00:08:31.020 --> 00:08:34.559
It's true, and it's really
the shame of our city.

00:08:34.559 --> 00:08:40.289
But even predominantly white
schools or predominantly Asian

00:08:40.289 --> 00:08:42.419
schools or predominantly
black and Latino

00:08:42.419 --> 00:08:47.430
schools still have lots
of different religions,

00:08:47.430 --> 00:08:49.810
lots of different languages.

00:08:49.810 --> 00:08:54.160
I was at PS 189 in Crown Heights
the other day in Brooklyn.

00:08:54.160 --> 00:08:58.200
It's 97% black and
Latino, but the children

00:08:58.200 --> 00:09:01.620
speak Spanish, English, creole.

00:09:01.620 --> 00:09:03.870
There's even some
Chinese kids there.

00:09:03.870 --> 00:09:05.760
There's a range of incomes.

00:09:05.760 --> 00:09:07.320
There's a pediatrician.

00:09:07.320 --> 00:09:11.220
There's a cab driver,
a home health aide.

00:09:11.220 --> 00:09:13.950
It's a school that
has served generations

00:09:13.950 --> 00:09:16.470
of parents in Crown Heights.

00:09:16.470 --> 00:09:18.870
And they have dual language
programs where children

00:09:18.870 --> 00:09:20.640
can learn Spanish and creole.

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:21.960
They even learn Latin.

00:09:21.960 --> 00:09:24.840
So that's a school
which in some ways

00:09:24.840 --> 00:09:29.850
is indeed highly segregated
and in other ways is diverse.

00:09:29.850 --> 00:09:34.470
I remember going to an all
black school in Brooklyn

00:09:34.470 --> 00:09:36.660
and asking the kids what
they liked about it.

00:09:36.660 --> 00:09:39.240
And they said, oh, I
love the diversity.

00:09:39.240 --> 00:09:41.980
And I said, what do you mean?

00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:44.370
And they said, oh, we have
kids from every single island

00:09:44.370 --> 00:09:45.240
in the Caribbean.

00:09:48.730 --> 00:09:51.580
Another reason to
choose a public school

00:09:51.580 --> 00:09:56.890
is kids need parents
who aren't stressed out.

00:09:56.890 --> 00:09:59.110
Commuting time really matters.

00:09:59.110 --> 00:10:02.350
If you're trying to decide
between a great school 20

00:10:02.350 --> 00:10:05.920
blocks away and a pretty good
school across the street,

00:10:05.920 --> 00:10:08.680
I would choose the
one across the street.

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:11.710
Another question is, if
you're working 60 hours a week

00:10:11.710 --> 00:10:14.590
to pay private school
tuition, maybe you're

00:10:14.590 --> 00:10:17.560
better off sending your
child to public school.

00:10:17.560 --> 00:10:20.650
If working part time means you
can go on an occasional field

00:10:20.650 --> 00:10:23.080
trip, volunteer
at the school, you

00:10:23.080 --> 00:10:26.940
may enjoy being with
your child, and that time

00:10:26.940 --> 00:10:28.730
can be very important.

00:10:28.730 --> 00:10:31.330
I also want to point out
that education is not

00:10:31.330 --> 00:10:36.790
just what you have from 9:00
AM to 3:00 PM 180 days a year.

00:10:36.790 --> 00:10:38.930
Just living in the
city of New York

00:10:38.930 --> 00:10:44.500
gives you access to resources
that people elsewhere

00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:48.820
don't have, the Natural
History Museum, the Bronx Zoo.

00:10:48.820 --> 00:10:54.490
My children danced with the
National Dance Institute.

00:10:54.490 --> 00:10:56.770
There are huge
numbers of resources

00:10:56.770 --> 00:11:02.470
that you can take advantage of
just by living in the school.

00:11:02.470 --> 00:11:05.380
Of course the argument
about the 60 hours a week

00:11:05.380 --> 00:11:06.610
may work the other way.

00:11:06.610 --> 00:11:07.900
If you're already working--

00:11:07.900 --> 00:11:10.540
I realized I'm talking
to Googlers here.

00:11:10.540 --> 00:11:12.580
If you're already
working 60 hours a week,

00:11:12.580 --> 00:11:15.370
you may want to choose private
because you don't have to be

00:11:15.370 --> 00:11:17.920
on top of everything at school.

00:11:17.920 --> 00:11:22.210
But what my point is is
consider your own convenience

00:11:22.210 --> 00:11:27.520
and your own levels of stress
when you're deciding on school.

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:29.650
The children are made
of rubber, and they

00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:33.800
can adapt to lots of
different situations.

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:35.320
Another thing I
want you to remember

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:38.500
is that no school is perfect.

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:41.590
As a parent, you have to
decide what you can live with,

00:11:41.590 --> 00:11:44.654
what you can supplement at home.

00:11:44.654 --> 00:11:47.195
There's some things you can fix,
and there's some things that

00:11:47.195 --> 00:11:48.269
you can't.

00:11:48.269 --> 00:11:50.560
You certainly don't want to
send your child to a school

00:11:50.560 --> 00:11:53.410
where there's lots of bullying,
or where the adults yell

00:11:53.410 --> 00:11:56.710
at the children, or where
teachers have low expectations

00:11:56.710 --> 00:12:00.940
and the children are overwhelmed
by the problems of poverty.

00:12:00.940 --> 00:12:03.880
My children's school had
physical education just one day

00:12:03.880 --> 00:12:05.110
a week.

00:12:05.110 --> 00:12:05.990
So what did we do?

00:12:05.990 --> 00:12:08.230
We supplemented with West
Side Soccer League, which

00:12:08.230 --> 00:12:12.730
is a volunteer, moms and dads
will coach kids on the weekend.

00:12:12.730 --> 00:12:14.535
They take up most
of the park space

00:12:14.535 --> 00:12:15.660
in the city on the weekend.

00:12:15.660 --> 00:12:18.130
You've probably seen them.

00:12:18.130 --> 00:12:19.750
If there's not
enough math drill,

00:12:19.750 --> 00:12:21.670
you can have flashcards at home.

00:12:21.670 --> 00:12:23.860
If there's not a
foreign language,

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:25.660
you can take the
whole family to France

00:12:25.660 --> 00:12:30.720
for three months for the price
of private school tuition.

00:12:30.720 --> 00:12:33.222
It also depends on your child.

00:12:33.222 --> 00:12:34.930
Some children are
like-- a nursery school

00:12:34.930 --> 00:12:36.550
teacher described this to me.

00:12:36.550 --> 00:12:39.100
Some children are
like dandelions.

00:12:39.100 --> 00:12:42.850
They're robust, and they can
flourish in lots of places.

00:12:42.850 --> 00:12:44.440
Others are more like orchids.

00:12:44.440 --> 00:12:47.380
They're delicate, and they need
just the right temperature.

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:51.580
Some schools do a good job with
children with special needs.

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:54.470
Others do not.

00:12:54.470 --> 00:12:58.330
So it depends a little bit
on your own family situation

00:12:58.330 --> 00:13:02.860
and on the what
your child is like.

00:13:02.860 --> 00:13:05.800
The most important thing,
a friend once told me,

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:08.830
is to find a school
that doesn't kill

00:13:08.830 --> 00:13:11.890
your child's natural curiosity.

00:13:11.890 --> 00:13:15.450
A lot of what children
learn in the early years

00:13:15.450 --> 00:13:17.400
is not-- particularly
in kindergarten,

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:19.120
it's not cognitive.

00:13:19.120 --> 00:13:22.780
It's social, learning how to
sit in a circle, how to share,

00:13:22.780 --> 00:13:24.489
how to develop
independence, things

00:13:24.489 --> 00:13:25.780
like how to tie your own shoes.

00:13:28.730 --> 00:13:30.410
The tone and climate
of a school may

00:13:30.410 --> 00:13:32.930
be more important than
the children's scores

00:13:32.930 --> 00:13:34.135
on standardized tests.

00:13:34.135 --> 00:13:36.760
Oh, and the scores, by the way,
tell you where a school's been.

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:40.670
It doesn't tell you necessarily
where a school is going.

00:13:40.670 --> 00:13:43.100
A school that's promising
and on its way up

00:13:43.100 --> 00:13:45.680
may provide a better
experience for your child

00:13:45.680 --> 00:13:49.490
than a complacent,
well-established school that's

00:13:49.490 --> 00:13:53.300
coasting on its reputation.

00:13:53.300 --> 00:13:55.854
So that's my pitch
on why public.

00:13:55.854 --> 00:13:57.770
Now I'm going to give
you the sort of the nuts

00:13:57.770 --> 00:14:02.240
and bolts of how to navigate
the New York City public school

00:14:02.240 --> 00:14:03.450
system.

00:14:03.450 --> 00:14:07.400
The good news is that all
four-year-olds are guaranteed

00:14:07.400 --> 00:14:09.680
a seat in pre-kindergarten.

00:14:09.680 --> 00:14:12.440
The bad news is it may not
be in the school closest

00:14:12.440 --> 00:14:13.664
to your home.

00:14:13.664 --> 00:14:15.080
If you're willing
to travel a bit,

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:17.660
you'll definitely get a spot.

00:14:17.660 --> 00:14:20.630
The applications
open in mid-January.

00:14:20.630 --> 00:14:22.880
The deadlines are at
the end of February.

00:14:22.880 --> 00:14:25.370
But if you're looking for
a school for your child

00:14:25.370 --> 00:14:27.380
this fall, take heart.

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:29.600
Seats open up in the
spring and the summer.

00:14:29.600 --> 00:14:32.720
For your child to
be eligible, he

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:36.260
needs to have his fourth
birthday by December 31.

00:14:36.260 --> 00:14:38.570
That means, and say if
he has a fall birthday,

00:14:38.570 --> 00:14:42.410
he'll actually start
pre-kindergarten

00:14:42.410 --> 00:14:45.620
when he's three.

00:14:45.620 --> 00:14:47.870
de Blasio has also
promised that he's

00:14:47.870 --> 00:14:51.290
going to have
pre-pre-kindergarten

00:14:51.290 --> 00:14:52.270
for three-year-olds.

00:14:52.270 --> 00:14:55.350
They're going to start in two
high-poverty districts, one

00:14:55.350 --> 00:14:58.580
in the South Bronx and one in
central Brooklyn in the fall.

00:14:58.580 --> 00:15:00.460
They haven't got money
for anything else,

00:15:00.460 --> 00:15:07.239
so I think asking the
federal government

00:15:07.239 --> 00:15:09.530
and the state for extra money
right now is probably not

00:15:09.530 --> 00:15:10.196
going to happen.

00:15:10.196 --> 00:15:13.730
But we do have pre-K
for four-year-olds.

00:15:13.730 --> 00:15:16.280
Not all of the
pre-kindergarten classes

00:15:16.280 --> 00:15:18.440
are in ordinary public schools.

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:20.940
In fact, most of them
are housed in child care

00:15:20.940 --> 00:15:25.400
centers or private nursery
schools or religious schools.

00:15:25.400 --> 00:15:27.740
You can see the pie chart here.

00:15:27.740 --> 00:15:31.730
The cities also opened what
they call pre-K centers.

00:15:31.730 --> 00:15:34.040
These are standalone
schools that your child

00:15:34.040 --> 00:15:36.290
will attend for just one year.

00:15:36.290 --> 00:15:38.870
We list some of our
favorites in the book.

00:15:38.870 --> 00:15:40.370
It's certainly a
good idea to visit,

00:15:40.370 --> 00:15:44.030
but most of the programs
we visit are pretty good.

00:15:44.030 --> 00:15:46.340
So that's pre-K.

00:15:46.340 --> 00:15:52.370
Elementary, this is where
the big kid school begins.

00:15:52.370 --> 00:15:56.120
And this is when
you're five years old,

00:15:56.120 --> 00:15:59.250
if you are five
before December 31,

00:15:59.250 --> 00:16:03.650
you're entitled to start
school in that September.

00:16:03.650 --> 00:16:09.590
So for the pre-K, you're
guaranteed a seat someplace,

00:16:09.590 --> 00:16:14.040
but not necessarily in your
zoned neighborhood school.

00:16:14.040 --> 00:16:15.950
In fact, most of
you will not have

00:16:15.950 --> 00:16:17.750
a seat in your zoned
neighborhood school.

00:16:17.750 --> 00:16:20.960
Some of them just have
18 seats for pre-K

00:16:20.960 --> 00:16:23.584
and 125 seats for kindergarten.

00:16:23.584 --> 00:16:25.250
So most of you are
going to have to look

00:16:25.250 --> 00:16:30.440
outside of your zoned public
school for pre-kindergarten.

00:16:30.440 --> 00:16:33.440
However, for elementary
school, most of you

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:37.340
have a zoned elementary
school, and your child

00:16:37.340 --> 00:16:39.920
is guaranteed admission there.

00:16:39.920 --> 00:16:42.170
One of the questions that
you gave me in advance

00:16:42.170 --> 00:16:43.820
was about wait lists.

00:16:43.820 --> 00:16:45.950
There are some schools
have wait lists.

00:16:45.950 --> 00:16:51.320
But honestly, almost all
of the wait lists clear.

00:16:51.320 --> 00:16:55.580
They ask parents to sign
up early, and many do.

00:16:55.580 --> 00:16:58.610
And they tell you that you're
on a wait list in March.

00:16:58.610 --> 00:17:00.920
But by September,
an awful lot of kids

00:17:00.920 --> 00:17:02.870
have either moved
out of the city,

00:17:02.870 --> 00:17:05.420
or chosen a private
school, or gone

00:17:05.420 --> 00:17:07.650
into a gifted and
talented program.

00:17:07.650 --> 00:17:09.890
So I would not worry
about-- there's

00:17:09.890 --> 00:17:15.200
a couple of schools that have
serious wait lists in Sunset

00:17:15.200 --> 00:17:16.910
Park, a couple in Queens.

00:17:16.910 --> 00:17:21.170
But by and large, it's
not going to be a problem.

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:26.440
The timeline is in--

00:17:26.440 --> 00:17:28.260
do I have another
slide for this?

00:17:28.260 --> 00:17:30.034
Nope, this is the districts.

00:17:33.850 --> 00:17:37.930
The timeline is you
apply in November

00:17:37.930 --> 00:17:39.910
if you want your
child to be considered

00:17:39.910 --> 00:17:42.850
for a gifted program.

00:17:42.850 --> 00:17:46.100
I'm not a big fan
of gifted education,

00:17:46.100 --> 00:17:49.270
but if your zoned neighborhood
school isn't adequate,

00:17:49.270 --> 00:17:52.880
it's certainly an option
that you should consider.

00:17:52.880 --> 00:17:55.720
The testing for children
for the gifted program

00:17:55.720 --> 00:17:58.480
is in January and February.

00:17:58.480 --> 00:18:02.590
And by January, then you submit
applications for other schools.

00:18:02.590 --> 00:18:05.020
Honestly the deadline
is way too early.

00:18:05.020 --> 00:18:07.210
Most people in the city
don't know in January

00:18:07.210 --> 00:18:09.220
what they're going to
be doing in September,

00:18:09.220 --> 00:18:12.160
and they almost
always extend it.

00:18:12.160 --> 00:18:13.930
By the end of March,
you'll find out

00:18:13.930 --> 00:18:15.790
where your child's
been assigned.

00:18:15.790 --> 00:18:18.070
If you're interested
in charter schools,

00:18:18.070 --> 00:18:22.030
the deadline is April 1.

00:18:22.030 --> 00:18:24.410
And then in April, you find
out if your children-- you

00:18:24.410 --> 00:18:24.910
know what?

00:18:24.910 --> 00:18:26.243
I'm making this too complicated.

00:18:26.243 --> 00:18:26.890
Read the book.

00:18:26.890 --> 00:18:29.270
Ask questions afterwards.

00:18:29.270 --> 00:18:31.270
I can see that the eyes
are getting a little bit

00:18:31.270 --> 00:18:33.430
