00:23:21.270 --> 00:23:25.380
I have a quick
question about, I know

00:23:25.380 --> 00:23:29.480
many parents, including my
wife actually, six years ago,

00:23:29.480 --> 00:23:32.190
I believe, told me that
we should move to a place

00:23:32.190 --> 00:23:33.480
where the school is 9 in 10.

00:23:33.480 --> 00:23:34.480
I said, what is 9 in 10?

00:23:34.480 --> 00:23:38.780
She said that Inside Schools
had the ranking system, 9 in 10,

00:23:38.780 --> 00:23:40.530
and that's how we ended
up buying a house.

00:23:40.530 --> 00:23:41.730
That was long, long ago.

00:23:41.730 --> 00:23:43.860
Now my son is five years old.

00:23:43.860 --> 00:23:46.910
So that was too much
planning towards the ranking.

00:23:46.910 --> 00:23:51.120
It But I still don't
understand how the numbers go,

00:23:51.120 --> 00:23:55.070
because that 9 in 10 became 6
in 10, then that became 8 in 10.

00:23:55.070 --> 00:23:58.830
So I learned that it's
not really test scores.

00:23:58.830 --> 00:24:01.650
And really, is it worth
giving that much weightage,

00:24:01.650 --> 00:24:02.520
depending on how--

00:24:02.520 --> 00:24:04.770
CLARA HEMPHILL: That's
a good question.

00:24:04.770 --> 00:24:06.150
We don't rank schools.

00:24:06.150 --> 00:24:10.410
It's our dread competitor,
greatschools.net.

00:24:10.410 --> 00:24:13.980
The difference between
greatschools.net and us

00:24:13.980 --> 00:24:17.670
is that we live in New York,
and we actually visit schools.

00:24:17.670 --> 00:24:26.520
And we base our reviews
on our visits to schools.

00:24:26.520 --> 00:24:31.590
Greatschools.net uses
two-year-old national data.

00:24:31.590 --> 00:24:34.680
It's a national website,
and it's largely

00:24:34.680 --> 00:24:41.640
based on test scores,
which is, as I said,

00:24:41.640 --> 00:24:44.790
where a school has been and
not where a school is going.

00:24:44.790 --> 00:24:48.180
I think test scores
are a rough--

00:24:48.180 --> 00:24:51.220
we have test scores
on our website,

00:24:51.220 --> 00:24:53.760
and I think they
are a rough measure

00:24:53.760 --> 00:24:56.010
of the quality of a school.

00:24:56.010 --> 00:24:59.310
If you have single digits of
children passing the tests,

00:24:59.310 --> 00:25:00.630
that's a problem.

00:25:00.630 --> 00:25:03.390
If you have 80% passing,
that's a good thing.

00:25:06.900 --> 00:25:11.010
On our website, we draw the
data from the Department

00:25:11.010 --> 00:25:15.640
of Ed surveys, which are given
to a million parents, teachers,

00:25:15.640 --> 00:25:18.450
and children themselves
at the schools.

00:25:18.450 --> 00:25:21.270
And the data that we
consider important,

00:25:21.270 --> 00:25:23.730
aside from the test
scores, is attendance--

00:25:23.730 --> 00:25:26.040
do most of the children show up?

00:25:26.040 --> 00:25:29.460
Teacher attendance-- do most
of the teachers show up?

00:25:29.460 --> 00:25:32.190
Teacher satisfaction--
do most of the teachers

00:25:32.190 --> 00:25:35.070
like the principal,
respect the principals?

00:25:35.070 --> 00:25:37.140
Do they work together as a team?

00:25:37.140 --> 00:25:41.640
So those are some of
the-- we have that data

00:25:41.640 --> 00:25:43.530
for every school in the city.

00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:50.850
And we have qualitative reviews
for about 800 of the schools.

00:25:50.850 --> 00:25:51.480
Does that help?

00:25:51.480 --> 00:25:54.767
AUDIENCE: Yep, thanks.

00:25:54.767 --> 00:25:56.350
AUDIENCE: So you
mentioned you weren't

00:25:56.350 --> 00:25:57.639
a big fan of gifted education.

00:25:57.639 --> 00:25:59.680
I was just wondering if
you could expand on that.

00:25:59.680 --> 00:26:01.805
Do you think the whole idea
is bad, or just the way

00:26:01.805 --> 00:26:03.645
it's actually implemented?

00:26:03.645 --> 00:26:05.020
CLARA HEMPHILL:
There are clearly

00:26:05.020 --> 00:26:08.332
some children who
need gifted education,

00:26:08.332 --> 00:26:09.790
as there are some
children who need

00:26:09.790 --> 00:26:11.860
any kind of special education.

00:26:11.860 --> 00:26:14.530
And in a room of Googlers,
there are probably

00:26:14.530 --> 00:26:17.380
some very gifted
children, I would guess.

00:26:23.890 --> 00:26:30.700
If your child is two standard
deviations from the mean,

00:26:30.700 --> 00:26:32.560
he may need gifted education.

00:26:32.560 --> 00:26:36.490
The problem is that
the tests are set up

00:26:36.490 --> 00:26:40.150
on national norms,
not local norms.

00:26:40.150 --> 00:26:42.340
So your child might
be two or three grade

00:26:42.340 --> 00:26:44.560
levels-- you might
live in the Bronx,

00:26:44.560 --> 00:26:47.140
and your child is two or three
grade levels ahead of the kids

00:26:47.140 --> 00:26:49.120
in the Bronx.

00:26:49.120 --> 00:26:52.120
But the city test
wouldn't recognize that.

00:26:52.120 --> 00:26:54.100
So there's almost
no kids in the Bronx

00:26:54.100 --> 00:26:57.760
who are considered eligible
for gifted education.

00:27:01.050 --> 00:27:06.550
And I think the tests also
reflect socioeconomics

00:27:06.550 --> 00:27:10.810
as much as they reflect
some kind of curiosity

00:27:10.810 --> 00:27:13.320
or natural ability.

00:27:13.320 --> 00:27:16.120
In more wealthy
neighborhoods, your child

00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:19.820
may be two standard
deviations from the mean,

00:27:19.820 --> 00:27:24.260
but everybody else is the
same in that neighborhood.

00:27:24.260 --> 00:27:28.390
So that District 2 on the Upper
East Side is like Lake Wobegon.

00:27:28.390 --> 00:27:29.620
Everybody's above average.

00:27:29.620 --> 00:27:33.530
But that doesn't mean that
they all need gifted education.

00:27:33.530 --> 00:27:36.010
I can always tell when I've
got a real one on the phone.

00:27:36.010 --> 00:27:39.100
The parent says that the
child has taught himself

00:27:39.100 --> 00:27:42.910
algebra at the age of three,
and he's having a little trouble

00:27:42.910 --> 00:27:45.920
making friends.

00:27:45.920 --> 00:27:47.890
And the parents desperately
want their children

00:27:47.890 --> 00:27:49.764
to be invited to
birthday parties.

00:27:49.764 --> 00:27:51.430
That's an example of
a child who I think

00:27:51.430 --> 00:27:53.500
needs the gifted education.

00:27:53.500 --> 00:27:58.030
Now, if we all had good
neighborhood schools,

00:27:58.030 --> 00:27:59.860
there would be a
very, very small need

00:27:59.860 --> 00:28:01.570
for gifted education.

00:28:01.570 --> 00:28:06.250
Unfortunately, the quality
of schools is really uneven.

00:28:06.250 --> 00:28:09.940
And gifted education is
a particularly good way

00:28:09.940 --> 00:28:11.800
to get out of a nasty
neighborhood school

00:28:11.800 --> 00:28:13.710
that you don't want
to send your child to.

00:28:13.710 --> 00:28:16.930
The other problem with
the gifted education

00:28:16.930 --> 00:28:18.670
is I think children
need to learn

00:28:18.670 --> 00:28:23.170
that hard work is what
matter, and you're not

00:28:23.170 --> 00:28:27.762
born with gifts as much.

00:28:27.762 --> 00:28:29.220
I mean, you may be
born with gifts,

00:28:29.220 --> 00:28:31.330
but what counts is
how hard you work.

00:28:31.330 --> 00:28:33.770
And in these gifted
programs, there's

00:28:33.770 --> 00:28:35.900
kind of a fear of falling.

00:28:35.900 --> 00:28:38.600
There's a fear of failure.

00:28:38.600 --> 00:28:42.800
Also I think the tests
measure a rather narrow range

00:28:42.800 --> 00:28:44.900
of academic skills.

00:28:44.900 --> 00:28:47.030
They don't test if
you're a great musician.

00:28:47.030 --> 00:28:49.160
They don't test if
you're a great artist.

00:28:49.160 --> 00:28:51.140
They don't test if
you're athletic.

00:28:51.140 --> 00:28:52.790
They don't test if
you're particularly

00:28:52.790 --> 00:28:58.430
good at making friends and
ending playground squabbles.

00:28:58.430 --> 00:29:04.520
So I want my children to be
exposed to all of those things

00:29:04.520 --> 00:29:08.275
and not just to kids who do
well on a particular test.

00:29:08.275 --> 00:29:09.650
The other thing
is I think giving

00:29:09.650 --> 00:29:13.970
the test to four-year-olds
is really too early.

00:29:13.970 --> 00:29:18.890
I just think that the predictive
quality of these tests

00:29:18.890 --> 00:29:21.410
is not that-- the tests
are not that accurate.

00:29:21.410 --> 00:29:24.290
And the divide between
the 99th percentile

00:29:24.290 --> 00:29:28.370
and the 98th percentile
of kids at the age of four

00:29:28.370 --> 00:29:29.955
is kind of ludicrous.

00:29:29.955 --> 00:29:31.580
The other thing is
a lot of what you're

00:29:31.580 --> 00:29:34.250
learning in elementary
school is not cognitive.

00:29:34.250 --> 00:29:37.860
It's how to tie your shoes,
how to sit in a circle,

00:29:37.860 --> 00:29:39.770
how to make friends,
how to get along

00:29:39.770 --> 00:29:41.190
with the classroom routines.

00:29:41.190 --> 00:29:46.560
So this is what I think about
early childhood education.

00:29:46.560 --> 00:29:50.150
I think by third, fourth,
fifth, sixth grade,

00:29:50.150 --> 00:29:55.340
a very good teacher can
reach a range of children.

00:29:55.340 --> 00:29:59.840
But the wider that
range is, the harder it

00:29:59.840 --> 00:30:05.000
is for a teacher to reach that.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:07.040
In my kindergarten,
what you'd want

00:30:07.040 --> 00:30:11.420
to ask of the school is, how
do you challenge children

00:30:11.420 --> 00:30:17.480
at the top, and how do you
give help to kids who need it?

00:30:17.480 --> 00:30:19.170
And your child might
need both, right?

00:30:19.170 --> 00:30:23.210
Your child might be a math whiz
who has trouble making friends.

00:30:23.210 --> 00:30:27.530
Or your child may be reading
"Harry Potter" in kindergarten

00:30:27.530 --> 00:30:29.120
but can't add, right?

00:30:29.120 --> 00:30:32.780
So your child can be
simultaneously gifted

00:30:32.780 --> 00:30:37.490
and struggling at the same time.

00:30:37.490 --> 00:30:40.190
My son was very good at puzzles.

00:30:40.190 --> 00:30:44.930
And when in kindergarten he
finished the 100-piece puzzle,

00:30:44.930 --> 00:30:48.980
the teacher would pull down
the 500-piece puzzle for him.

00:30:48.980 --> 00:30:53.480
When you look in classrooms, you
want to see a range of books.

00:30:53.480 --> 00:30:55.760
If everybody is
reading the same book,

00:30:55.760 --> 00:30:58.580
that's probably
not a good place.

00:30:58.580 --> 00:31:01.200
But if some kids are reading
"Frog and Toad" and other kids

00:31:01.200 --> 00:31:03.920
are reading "Charlotte's
Web," that's a sign.

00:31:03.920 --> 00:31:06.140
If you look at the
writing on the board

00:31:06.140 --> 00:31:08.600
and you see some kids
are writing five pages

00:31:08.600 --> 00:31:11.000
and some kids are
writing three paragraphs,

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.610
that's a sign that
the school is adapting

00:31:13.610 --> 00:31:15.890
to kids with different needs.

00:31:15.890 --> 00:31:20.259
So of course you want your
child to be challenged

00:31:20.259 --> 00:31:21.800
if he's very bright,
and you want him

00:31:21.800 --> 00:31:24.440
to get the help if he needs it.

00:31:24.440 --> 00:31:26.120
But that doesn't
necessarily mean

00:31:26.120 --> 00:31:29.660
he needs to be
segregated in a classroom

00:31:29.660 --> 00:31:33.359
with other kids who do
well on this academic test.

00:31:33.359 --> 00:31:35.654
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:31:35.654 --> 00:31:38.410
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:31:38.410 --> 00:31:41.461
So the school that we're
zoned for is relatively new.

00:31:41.461 --> 00:31:43.460
It was just launched like
four years ago, maybe,

00:31:43.460 --> 00:31:45.660
so I think there's not a lot
of information on it yet.

00:31:45.660 --> 00:31:46.290
CLARA HEMPHILL: Which school?

00:31:46.290 --> 00:31:48.165
AUDIENCE: It's the School
for Social Action--

00:31:48.165 --> 00:31:49.498
CLARA HEMPHILL: Yeah, I know it.

00:31:49.498 --> 00:31:51.130
AUDIENCE: --527, I think it is.

00:31:51.130 --> 00:31:54.550
So we ideally want to send-- our
daughter is only 7 months old.

00:31:54.550 --> 00:31:56.620
But we want to send
her there, but we're

00:31:56.620 --> 00:31:58.870
being told by a lot of people
to keep our options open

00:31:58.870 --> 00:32:00.869
and make sure we're
planning for the possibility

00:32:00.869 --> 00:32:04.970
of a gifted and talented
program or a private school.

00:32:04.970 --> 00:32:06.580
So I guess my
question is twofold.

00:32:06.580 --> 00:32:09.302
What are your thoughts
on that and knowing

00:32:09.302 --> 00:32:10.510
that our daughter's so young?

00:32:10.510 --> 00:32:11.530
What are the things
that we should

00:32:11.530 --> 00:32:13.238
be thinking about
right now to set her up

00:32:13.238 --> 00:32:14.470
for whatever options?

00:32:14.470 --> 00:32:16.512
But ideally wanting to
send her to public school,

00:32:16.512 --> 00:32:19.011
are there things that we should
be thinking about doing now?

00:32:19.011 --> 00:32:21.820
CLARA HEMPHILL: If you can
afford to stay in District 2,

00:32:21.820 --> 00:32:23.560
I'd stay put.

00:32:23.560 --> 00:32:26.530
District 2 not only has
terrific elementary schools.

00:32:26.530 --> 00:32:29.290
It also has good middle
schools and good high schools,

00:32:29.290 --> 00:32:34.000
which is not universally
the case at all.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:38.322
Then I like 527 a lot.

00:32:38.322 --> 00:32:40.280
It's a shade more
traditional than some-- well,

00:32:40.280 --> 00:32:42.610
I won't get into details
about individual schools.

00:32:42.610 --> 00:32:45.472
But in your
district, I like 527.

00:32:45.472 --> 00:32:46.180
It's in the book.

00:32:46.180 --> 00:32:47.230
You can read about it.

00:32:47.230 --> 00:32:50.200
There's also a gifted
program a few blocks away.

00:32:50.200 --> 00:32:53.380
There's two gifted programs a
few blocks away, both of which

00:32:53.380 --> 00:32:54.215
I like very well.

00:32:54.215 --> 00:32:55.840
AUDIENCE: So are
there things we should

00:32:55.840 --> 00:32:57.760
be thinking about doing,
though, to make sure

00:32:57.760 --> 00:33:00.010
that she's prepared
for the application

00:33:00.010 --> 00:33:02.504
process for gifted and
talented or for getting her

00:33:02.504 --> 00:33:03.670
ready for elementary school?

00:33:03.670 --> 00:33:05.650
Because I've just heard from
people in the building who

00:33:05.650 --> 00:33:08.080
are saying they send their
kids to gifted and talented,

00:33:08.080 --> 00:33:09.430
and they're like, oh there's
all these things you have to do,

00:33:09.430 --> 00:33:11.221
these classes you have
to take to make sure

00:33:11.221 --> 00:33:14.710
that they're on the
resume for a two-year-old.

00:33:14.710 --> 00:33:17.080
CLARA HEMPHILL: Yeah, I
think it's kind of sick.

00:33:17.080 --> 00:33:19.475
I want to let children
be children, right?

00:33:19.475 --> 00:33:20.590
AUDIENCE: I agree.

00:33:20.590 --> 00:33:24.730
CLARA HEMPHILL: And I will
encourage you to resist that.

00:33:24.730 --> 00:33:28.480
My son, I thought he was gifted.

00:33:28.480 --> 00:33:31.960
You know, he was doing the
big puzzles in kindergarten.

00:33:31.960 --> 00:33:36.040
But at the age of four, he
was still throwing blocks.

00:33:36.040 --> 00:33:37.780
And the thought of
having him sit down

00:33:37.780 --> 00:33:41.650
with a stranger and a pencil and
paper test just seemed insane.

00:33:41.650 --> 00:33:47.080
So yeah, sure,
there are people who

00:33:47.080 --> 00:33:50.080
will charge you lots of money
to prepare for this test.

00:33:50.080 --> 00:33:53.920
But I would strongly
discourage it, particularly

00:33:53.920 --> 00:33:55.690
because you live
in a neighborhood

00:33:55.690 --> 00:33:57.379
where the zoned
schools are fine.

00:33:57.379 --> 00:33:59.670
In neighborhoods where the
zoned schools are not fine--

00:33:59.670 --> 00:34:02.890
I don't mean to trash gifted
and talented across the board.

00:34:02.890 --> 00:34:04.030
Easy for me to say.

00:34:04.030 --> 00:34:06.880
My kids went to the local
school, and it was great.

00:34:06.880 --> 00:34:10.868
For a lot of people, the gifted
schools are a good option.

00:34:10.868 --> 00:34:12.409
AUDIENCE: Sorry,
one last thing then.

00:34:12.409 --> 00:34:15.919
If the baby-- you mentioned
that the cutoff is December 31.

00:34:15.919 --> 00:34:18.210
There's a lot of theories
about keeping your child back

00:34:18.210 --> 00:34:19.230
or advancing them.

00:34:19.230 --> 00:34:20.855
But it sounds like
my reading showed me

00:34:20.855 --> 00:34:23.229
that in public schools you
don't really have that choice.

00:34:23.229 --> 00:34:25.250
Is that true, or can you
hold your child back?

00:34:25.250 --> 00:34:25.790
CLARA HEMPHILL: You cannot.

00:34:25.790 --> 00:34:26.300
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:34:26.300 --> 00:34:27.934
CLARA HEMPHILL: You're
stuck with the--

00:34:27.934 --> 00:34:29.059
AUDIENCE: Starting at four.

00:34:29.059 --> 00:34:31.490
CLARA HEMPHILL: Yeah, so this
is called redshirting, where

00:34:31.490 --> 00:34:33.864
you hold the kids back a yeah,
with the idea that they'll

00:34:33.864 --> 00:34:35.830
be bigger and
stronger and smarter.

00:34:35.830 --> 00:34:37.219
And it's the same
group of people

00:34:37.219 --> 00:34:38.510
who are telling
you to get the test

00:34:38.510 --> 00:34:39.320
prep for your seven-month-old.

00:34:39.320 --> 00:34:39.986
AUDIENCE: It is.

00:34:43.198 --> 00:34:44.989
CLARA HEMPHILL: I have
a November birthday,

00:34:44.989 --> 00:34:47.060
so my daughter was
the November birthday.

00:34:47.060 --> 00:34:49.590
And she was pretty
tiny for kindergarten,

00:34:49.590 --> 00:34:52.800
and she was pretty exhausted
at the end of the day.

00:34:52.800 --> 00:34:55.922
So I understand the--

00:34:55.922 --> 00:34:56.630
AUDIENCE: Theory?

00:34:56.630 --> 00:34:59.960
CLARA HEMPHILL: Yeah, I
understand the impulse to--

00:34:59.960 --> 00:35:04.340
I mean, I think it's actually
there are political reasons why

00:35:04.340 --> 00:35:06.500
these things are set up
that don't necessarily

00:35:06.500 --> 00:35:10.310
have to do with pedagogy
or child development.

00:35:10.310 --> 00:35:18.140
I hope the question you could
ask at 527 or any other school

00:35:18.140 --> 00:35:22.865
is, my child has a
November birthday.

00:35:25.430 --> 00:35:28.907
How do you adapt for
younger children?

00:35:28.907 --> 00:35:30.365
You know, do they
have a rest time?

00:35:37.010 --> 00:35:39.760
Can they accommodate a child
who's a little bit younger?

00:35:39.760 --> 00:35:41.930
And see what they answer.

00:35:41.930 --> 00:35:43.970
I mean, I think that's
a valid question.

00:35:43.970 --> 00:35:45.530
But they won't let you
redshirt them, unfortunately.

00:35:45.530 --> 00:35:47.113
AUDIENCE: We don't
have an option, OK.

00:35:47.113 --> 00:35:48.106
All right, thank you.

00:35:48.106 --> 00:35:48.522
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:35:48.522 --> 00:35:49.313
CLARA HEMPHILL: Hi.

00:35:49.313 --> 00:35:51.320
AUDIENCE: A couple of
questions, if I may.

00:35:51.320 --> 00:35:54.560
First, I'd love to hear your
thoughts on non-zoned district

00:35:54.560 --> 00:35:55.370
schools.

00:35:55.370 --> 00:35:56.980
Why do they exist,
and what steps

00:35:56.980 --> 00:35:58.730
can one take if there's
a great one nearby

00:35:58.730 --> 00:36:00.980
that you want to
get your kid into?

00:36:00.980 --> 00:36:04.910
And then second, the
school in my zone

