00:39:44.240 --> 00:39:47.990
So I think that's
a wonderful trend.

00:39:47.990 --> 00:39:50.690
I think the trend towards
progressive education

00:39:50.690 --> 00:39:51.470
is a good one.

00:39:51.470 --> 00:39:54.290
I think children
learn through doing.

00:39:54.290 --> 00:39:56.180
They learn through play.

00:39:56.180 --> 00:39:58.850
They learn by putting
together blocks.

00:39:58.850 --> 00:40:03.140
They learn engineering and math
skills with blocks and Lego.

00:40:03.140 --> 00:40:06.160
So I like classrooms that
have a lot of blocks and Lego,

00:40:06.160 --> 00:40:07.910
rather than classrooms
for the little kids

00:40:07.910 --> 00:40:10.580
that have lots of pencil
and paper exercises.

00:40:10.580 --> 00:40:13.670
I like schools where
the children read what

00:40:13.670 --> 00:40:15.050
they call authentic literature.

00:40:15.050 --> 00:40:17.000
That is children's
picture books and books

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:18.560
that you might read for fun.

00:40:18.560 --> 00:40:22.710
I think the extent to
which that's increasing.

00:40:22.710 --> 00:40:24.590
I think is a very good idea.

00:40:24.590 --> 00:40:26.390
What I don't like
is the obsession

00:40:26.390 --> 00:40:28.520
with standardized tests.

00:40:28.520 --> 00:40:32.330
Some schools have become
just test prep hell

00:40:32.330 --> 00:40:36.200
where the kids work for
hours and hours and hours

00:40:36.200 --> 00:40:39.774
learning how to fill
out bubble sheets.

00:40:39.774 --> 00:40:40.482
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:40:44.230 --> 00:40:44.880
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:40:44.880 --> 00:40:48.310
I have maybe two
questions, if there's time,

00:40:48.310 --> 00:40:51.200
about reading between
the lines on a school.

00:40:51.200 --> 00:40:53.610
One question is,
how do you determine

00:40:53.610 --> 00:40:55.480
if a school is improving?

00:40:55.480 --> 00:40:57.200
Because you mentioned
how it's not about

00:40:57.200 --> 00:40:59.440
where the school has been.

00:40:59.440 --> 00:41:01.450
CLARA HEMPHILL: That's
a really good question.

00:41:01.450 --> 00:41:07.840
In terms of data, I look to see
if enrollment is increasing.

00:41:07.840 --> 00:41:11.740
That's usually a sign of
parents voting with their feet.

00:41:11.740 --> 00:41:13.930
I look to see if
attendance is improving.

00:41:13.930 --> 00:41:16.885
Before the test scores
go up, you've got to--

00:41:16.885 --> 00:41:19.480
some of the public schools
have very, very high rates

00:41:19.480 --> 00:41:21.400
of absenteeism.

00:41:21.400 --> 00:41:23.380
And that's a sign
that the kids are not

00:41:23.380 --> 00:41:25.660
happy to be there,
and so when you

00:41:25.660 --> 00:41:28.190
see the attendance going up.

00:41:28.190 --> 00:41:33.500
The most important thing
is an effective principal,

00:41:33.500 --> 00:41:34.280
hands down.

00:41:34.280 --> 00:41:38.690
A good principal will
attract good teachers

00:41:38.690 --> 00:41:41.720
and encourage them to
work together as a team.

00:41:41.720 --> 00:41:45.780
A bad principal can dismantle
a good school just as quickly.

00:41:45.780 --> 00:41:50.030
So leadership is all, and you
can usually feel the difference

00:41:50.030 --> 00:41:53.570
within about a couple of weeks
of the new principal coming

00:41:53.570 --> 00:41:54.590
to town.

00:41:54.590 --> 00:42:00.260
So in terms of the data, we do
look at teacher satisfaction

00:42:00.260 --> 00:42:02.690
with the principal is
one thing to look at,

00:42:02.690 --> 00:42:06.480
which we have on our website.

00:42:06.480 --> 00:42:12.650
And those are the
signs that a school is

00:42:12.650 --> 00:42:14.560
moving in the right direction.

00:42:14.560 --> 00:42:20.150
Again, schools
that are improving

00:42:20.150 --> 00:42:22.850
start getting better
in the lower grades

00:42:22.850 --> 00:42:24.920
and build up one by one.

00:42:24.920 --> 00:42:29.960
So if you see a good
pre-K and kindergarten

00:42:29.960 --> 00:42:34.010
but the fifth grade is not
so hot, that may be OK.

00:42:34.010 --> 00:42:37.880
It could be that they're
building from the bottom up.

00:42:37.880 --> 00:42:39.870
So look for the lower grades.

00:42:39.870 --> 00:42:40.550
Is that helpful?

00:42:40.550 --> 00:42:41.591
AUDIENCE: That was great.

00:42:41.591 --> 00:42:43.130
Another quick question then.

00:42:46.215 --> 00:42:49.090
So speaking of someone
who would be parents

00:42:49.090 --> 00:42:54.110
of mixed-race children,
I'm thinking of,

00:42:54.110 --> 00:42:56.710
how could you determine if
there's the educational quality

00:42:56.710 --> 00:42:58.769
available for all children?

00:42:58.769 --> 00:43:00.560
Because sometimes some
schools we looked at

00:43:00.560 --> 00:43:04.760
we'd think some anxiety if, oh,
their rating on School Crusher

00:43:04.760 --> 00:43:05.750
or whatever--

00:43:05.750 --> 00:43:08.900
their rating on some
other website is high,

00:43:08.900 --> 00:43:11.810
but then they see like really
significant segregation

00:43:11.810 --> 00:43:14.060
at the gas levels
of other things.

00:43:14.060 --> 00:43:16.820
So how could you read into
whether it's a good education

00:43:16.820 --> 00:43:19.120
for all of the students there?

00:43:19.120 --> 00:43:22.310
CLARA HEMPHILL: Yeah, I
talk to parents about that.

00:43:22.310 --> 00:43:22.910
It's funny.

00:43:22.910 --> 00:43:26.180
I went to PS 75, which
was one of my slides,

00:43:26.180 --> 00:43:31.300
with an African-American
staff member, and 166.

00:43:31.300 --> 00:43:36.290
75 is mostly black and Latino,
and 166 is mostly white.

00:43:36.290 --> 00:43:39.200
And she felt right
away a different vibe

00:43:39.200 --> 00:43:41.210
in the building
about how welcoming

00:43:41.210 --> 00:43:44.120
they are to people of color.

00:43:44.120 --> 00:43:50.960
But a lot of the schools
that are multi-racial do

00:43:50.960 --> 00:43:54.140
have lots of
multi-racial families

00:43:54.140 --> 00:43:56.060
also, because for them
it's very important.

00:43:56.060 --> 00:44:00.710
You know, if you have a black
mother and a white father,

00:44:00.710 --> 00:44:02.980
you may not want your child
in an all black school,

00:44:02.980 --> 00:44:06.590
but you don't want your child
in an all white school either.

00:44:06.590 --> 00:44:09.995
So I would ask for the parents.

00:44:14.210 --> 00:44:15.530
I should have brought--

00:44:15.530 --> 00:44:19.070
I'll send you a link to our
report on integrated schools

00:44:19.070 --> 00:44:21.650
that work, which is on the
Center for New York City

00:44:21.650 --> 00:44:22.700
Affairs website.

00:44:22.700 --> 00:44:25.760
And one of the things
that really matters

00:44:25.760 --> 00:44:30.584
is that the principal wants
the school to be integrated.

00:44:30.584 --> 00:44:32.500
You'd be surprised at
the number of principals

00:44:32.500 --> 00:44:35.410
who really don't care and are
happy with whatever the status

00:44:35.410 --> 00:44:36.242
quo is.

00:44:41.170 --> 00:44:42.830
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:44:42.830 --> 00:44:45.360
I'm in the middle of
going through the process

00:44:45.360 --> 00:44:46.465
with my four-year-old.

00:44:46.465 --> 00:44:48.590
So I was just wondering if
you had any more insight

00:44:48.590 --> 00:44:52.100
or could explain more about
the wait list situation

00:44:52.100 --> 00:44:54.200
and how that movement works.

00:44:54.200 --> 00:44:57.170
Because being in
May now, and we're

00:44:57.170 --> 00:44:59.294
on the wait list at
five different programs.

00:44:59.294 --> 00:45:01.460
CLARA HEMPHILL: Wait list
at five different programs

00:45:01.460 --> 00:45:02.570
for pre-K, or for--

00:45:02.570 --> 00:45:06.110
AUDIENCE: For pre-K,
and our wait lists,

00:45:06.110 --> 00:45:09.380
when I call the schools,
we're like 114 on the list

00:45:09.380 --> 00:45:12.070
and number 42 on the list.

00:45:12.070 --> 00:45:12.682
And--

00:45:12.682 --> 00:45:14.640
CLARA HEMPHILL: For pre-K
you're talking about.

00:45:14.640 --> 00:45:14.910
AUDIENCE: For pre-K.

00:45:14.910 --> 00:45:16.493
CLARA HEMPHILL: Yeah,
when I was being

00:45:16.493 --> 00:45:19.160
blase about the wait lists, I
was talking about kindergarten.

00:45:19.160 --> 00:45:19.730
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:45:19.730 --> 00:45:22.229
CLARA HEMPHILL: Pre-K it's a
whole different kettle of fish.

00:45:22.229 --> 00:45:26.910
You might have 18 seats and
500 kids, applying, so--

00:45:26.910 --> 00:45:29.224
AUDIENCE: So those
lists don't move then.

00:45:29.224 --> 00:45:30.390
CLARA HEMPHILL: They don't--

00:45:30.390 --> 00:45:32.090
let's talk afterwards
a little bit

00:45:32.090 --> 00:45:33.804
about your particular situation.

00:45:33.804 --> 00:45:35.720
AUDIENCE: And then how
do you manage between--

00:45:35.720 --> 00:45:39.050
so because pre-K is so
different than kindergarten,

00:45:39.050 --> 00:45:41.336
my understanding from
everyone I hear that is you

00:45:41.336 --> 00:45:43.669
have to go through this all
over again for kindergarten.

00:45:43.669 --> 00:45:45.200
CLARA HEMPHILL: Isn't it awful?

00:45:45.200 --> 00:45:46.450
Do you believe it?

00:45:46.450 --> 00:45:48.620
Yeah, and then middle
school and high school too.

00:45:48.620 --> 00:45:50.420
AUDIENCE: So how
do you even plan

00:45:50.420 --> 00:45:54.410
what pre-K you would want
to go to for consistency's

00:45:54.410 --> 00:45:55.847
sake for your kid?

00:45:55.847 --> 00:45:57.680
CLARA HEMPHILL: I mean,
consistency is nice.

00:45:57.680 --> 00:45:59.380
It would be great.

00:45:59.380 --> 00:46:01.370
AUDIENCE: So you just--
it's not realistic.

00:46:03.535 --> 00:46:04.910
CLARA HEMPHILL:
I talk to parents

00:46:04.910 --> 00:46:08.870
who have private nursery
school for the three-year-old

00:46:08.870 --> 00:46:11.630
and then public pre-K
for the four-year-old

00:46:11.630 --> 00:46:13.960
and then a public school
for when he's five.

00:46:13.960 --> 00:46:17.130
And moving three times in three
years would drive me nuts.

00:46:17.130 --> 00:46:18.710
So I can understand--

00:46:18.710 --> 00:46:20.780
I think continuity
is probably worth

00:46:20.780 --> 00:46:26.367
spending a little money for if
you have to, but more for you

00:46:26.367 --> 00:46:27.200
than for your child.

00:46:27.200 --> 00:46:30.320
I mean, I think your child
will probably adjust.

00:46:30.320 --> 00:46:33.770
The pre-K situation, it's only
been around for two years.

00:46:33.770 --> 00:46:37.460
They created 70,000 seats
practically overnight.

00:46:37.460 --> 00:46:39.525
That it's functioning
is a miracle.

00:46:42.320 --> 00:46:45.169
But certain
neighborhoods this city,

00:46:45.169 --> 00:46:46.460
there are just long wait lists.

00:46:46.460 --> 00:46:48.300
And they haven't
figured it out yet.

00:46:48.300 --> 00:46:49.300
AUDIENCE: It's shocking.

00:46:49.300 --> 00:46:50.050
But thank you.

00:46:50.050 --> 00:46:51.320
CLARA HEMPHILL: Yeah, sorry.

00:46:51.320 --> 00:46:51.710
Yeah.

00:46:51.710 --> 00:46:52.990
AUDIENCE: So you
said several times,

00:46:52.990 --> 00:46:54.698
the principal's the
most important thing.

00:46:54.698 --> 00:46:56.990
And you said, the principal
can make it happen.

00:46:56.990 --> 00:46:58.950
The school across
the street from us--

00:46:58.950 --> 00:47:01.122
it's PS 38, the
Pacific in Brooklyn--

00:47:01.122 --> 00:47:02.580
all the comments
talk about trouble

00:47:02.580 --> 00:47:05.060
with the administration and
the principal not being good.

00:47:05.060 --> 00:47:07.559
Is there something that you can
do about that, or is it just

00:47:07.559 --> 00:47:10.316
you avoid the school,
or I don't know--

00:47:10.316 --> 00:47:11.690
CLARA HEMPHILL:
Parents can lobby

00:47:11.690 --> 00:47:13.580
to get rid of a principal.

00:47:13.580 --> 00:47:16.880
They succeeded at 282,
which is in Park Slope,

00:47:16.880 --> 00:47:20.180
not too far from you.

00:47:20.180 --> 00:47:23.270
At 38, they're trying to
work around the principal.

00:47:23.270 --> 00:47:25.040
There are a couple
of schools that

00:47:25.040 --> 00:47:29.010
managed to build
a cohesive staff

00:47:29.010 --> 00:47:31.580
despite an inadequate principal.

00:47:31.580 --> 00:47:34.470
But then you have
to figure out why--

00:47:34.470 --> 00:47:38.060
some parents have also gotten
rid of terrible district

00:47:38.060 --> 00:47:39.290
superintendents.

00:47:39.290 --> 00:47:42.040
In Washington Heights,
parents united to get rid of.

00:47:42.040 --> 00:47:46.512
So, yeah, get rid of or work
around are the two answers.

00:47:46.512 --> 00:47:47.970
AUDIENCE: Does
working around work?

00:47:47.970 --> 00:47:49.295
Would you think that
school can be functional,

00:47:49.295 --> 00:47:50.920
or is it really it's
kind of in trouble

00:47:50.920 --> 00:47:52.154
with a principle like that?

00:47:52.154 --> 00:47:54.570
CLARA HEMPHILL: I think you
should talk to the parents who

00:47:54.570 --> 00:47:57.740
are there every day.

00:47:57.740 --> 00:47:59.965
I agree with your assessment.

00:47:59.965 --> 00:48:01.340
That said, there
are some parents

00:48:01.340 --> 00:48:02.923
who are very happy
with the situation.

00:48:05.820 --> 00:48:07.570
AUDIENCE: I wanted to
go back a little bit

00:48:07.570 --> 00:48:10.920
to the gifted and very high
functioning district school

00:48:10.920 --> 00:48:11.420
question.

00:48:11.420 --> 00:48:14.682
So I went to a public magnet
school that was amazing,

00:48:14.682 --> 00:48:16.390
and it was a really
good experience, very

00:48:16.390 --> 00:48:17.935
along the lines of Stuyvesant.

00:48:20.725 --> 00:48:22.630
And where I came from,
there was definitely

00:48:22.630 --> 00:48:24.280
a concept of feeder
schools, that there

00:48:24.280 --> 00:48:26.117
were middle schools
that gave rise

00:48:26.117 --> 00:48:27.700
to most of the high
schools, and there

00:48:27.700 --> 00:48:29.283
were elementary
schools that gave rise

00:48:29.283 --> 00:48:30.640
to most of the middle schools.

00:48:30.640 --> 00:48:33.190
Is there a feeder
school style setup

00:48:33.190 --> 00:48:34.580
here for the high schools?

00:48:34.580 --> 00:48:35.860
CLARA HEMPHILL: Alas, yes.

00:48:35.860 --> 00:48:36.780
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:48:36.780 --> 00:48:38.530
CLARA HEMPHILL: Another
one of our reports

00:48:38.530 --> 00:48:40.630
on the Center for New
York City Affairs website

00:48:40.630 --> 00:48:45.250
shows you what middle school
feeders there are to Stuyvesant

00:48:45.250 --> 00:48:47.830
and Brooklyn Tech and the
specialized high schools.

00:48:47.830 --> 00:48:52.120
So yes, but you don't have
to worry in kindergarten.

00:48:52.120 --> 00:48:52.670
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:48:52.670 --> 00:48:53.670
CLARA HEMPHILL: I think.

00:48:53.670 --> 00:48:55.086
AUDIENCE: But I
guess do they tend

00:48:55.086 --> 00:48:57.940
to be the sort of really
good neighborhood schools,

00:48:57.940 --> 00:49:00.735
or do they tend to be gifted
schools, or is it a mix?

00:49:00.735 --> 00:49:02.860
CLARA HEMPHILL: Don't worry
about it in elementary.

00:49:02.860 --> 00:49:03.420
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:49:03.420 --> 00:49:05.419
CLARA HEMPHILL: You know,
call me in five years,

00:49:05.419 --> 00:49:07.330
and we'll work it out.

00:49:07.330 --> 00:49:09.790
I'm not pretending the system
is equitable and works well

00:49:09.790 --> 00:49:10.450
for everybody.

00:49:10.450 --> 00:49:12.484
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:49:12.484 --> 00:49:14.650
CLARA HEMPHILL: We have
three more minutes, I guess.

00:49:14.650 --> 00:49:15.249
Yes.

00:49:15.249 --> 00:49:16.790
AUDIENCE: OK, so I
grew up in Europe,

00:49:16.790 --> 00:49:19.206
and I'm a lot more familiar
with the school systems there.

00:49:19.206 --> 00:49:20.920
A lot of things
are different here.

00:49:20.920 --> 00:49:22.795
Two things that we
haven't really touched on.

00:49:22.795 --> 00:49:27.730
One of them was that we learned
that classes get new teachers

00:49:27.730 --> 00:49:31.600
every year instead of
one teacher taking them

00:49:31.600 --> 00:49:34.120
throughout the first
five years of school.

00:49:34.120 --> 00:49:38.440
Is that true across the
board in most public schools,

00:49:38.440 --> 00:49:41.020
or are there differences,
or what's your opinion?

00:49:43.875 --> 00:49:45.250
CLARA HEMPHILL:
Some schools have

00:49:45.250 --> 00:49:49.090
what they call looping, which is
I teach kindergarten this year

00:49:49.090 --> 00:49:51.016
and first grade next
year, and then I

00:49:51.016 --> 00:49:52.890
go back to kindergarten
and then first grade.

00:49:52.890 --> 00:49:57.420
So you have the same
teacher for two years.

00:49:57.420 --> 00:50:00.107
And if you put looping
into our search engine,

00:50:00.107 --> 00:50:01.690
you might find some
schools like that.

00:50:01.690 --> 00:50:03.670
Or in the book you can see some.

00:50:03.670 --> 00:50:05.560
The other thing that
a few schools have

00:50:05.560 --> 00:50:07.810
is what they call
bridge classes, where

00:50:07.810 --> 00:50:11.440
you have both kindergarten and
first grade in one classroom,

00:50:11.440 --> 00:50:13.960
and you stay in that classroom
with the same teacher for two

00:50:13.960 --> 00:50:15.010
years.

00:50:15.010 --> 00:50:16.670
So we do have some of that.

00:50:16.670 --> 00:50:18.820
Rudolf Steiner
School is private.

00:50:18.820 --> 00:50:23.290
It's the only one I
know of that keeps

00:50:23.290 --> 00:50:26.500
the kids for the whole of
their elementary school.

00:50:26.500 --> 00:50:30.780
The New American Academy might
do that as well in Brooklyn.

00:50:30.780 --> 00:50:32.530
I think they may have
that European model.

00:50:32.530 --> 00:50:34.696
AUDIENCE: But you don't
think there's value in that,

00:50:34.696 --> 00:50:37.370
or it's just not common, or--

00:50:37.370 --> 00:50:40.020
CLARA HEMPHILL: Oh, sure, I
mean, like any of these things,

00:50:40.020 --> 00:50:43.017
there's advantages
and drawbacks.

00:50:43.017 --> 00:50:45.100
AUDIENCE: And the other
thing I wanted to touch on

00:50:45.100 --> 00:50:47.410
is about the PTA,
where people ask

00:50:47.410 --> 00:50:50.490
how they can get involved and
do something for the school.

00:50:50.490 --> 00:50:52.840
I sort of want to
ask the opposite.

00:50:52.840 --> 00:50:56.270
In Europe, schools work, and you
can get involved a little bit.

00:50:56.270 --> 00:51:00.190
But I sometimes feel there
is an expectation or pressure

00:51:00.190 --> 00:51:01.780
for people to get involved.

00:51:01.780 --> 00:51:04.760
And even though this isn't
like a private preschool,

00:51:04.760 --> 00:51:09.237
that parents who don't get
involved are called out,

00:51:09.237 --> 00:51:09.820
or it's like--

00:51:09.820 --> 00:51:11.891
I'm wondering how this happens.

00:51:11.891 --> 00:51:13.390
CLARA HEMPHILL:
This, I think it's--

00:51:13.390 --> 00:51:16.360
I mean, the other difference
between the United States

00:51:16.360 --> 00:51:19.750
and Europe is that
our schools are

00:51:19.750 --> 00:51:24.220
supported through local
taxes, mostly property taxes.

00:51:24.220 --> 00:51:27.730
And in most countries
of the world,

00:51:27.730 --> 00:51:30.610
it's a national system
where all the teachers

00:51:30.610 --> 00:51:34.070
get the same pay and the schools
all get the same resources.

00:51:34.070 --> 00:51:36.280
So what we do in
New York City is

